{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"98817a1f-adc8-461d-b101-87dfa35412b6","content":"For .NET 8 on Windows with admin access, **`dotnet-trace`** is the best starting point — it's lightweight, .NET-aware, and doesn't require installing heavy tools like PerfView or ETW sessions.\n\n### Install & Collect\n\n```powershell\n# Install the tool (one-time)\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n\n# Find your process ID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# Collect a 30-second CPU profile\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file you can open in **Visual Studio** (Diagnostics Hub) or **PerfView**.\n\n### If you need deeper OS-level detail\n\nUse **PerfView** (free Microsoft tool) for kernel + managed combined traces:\n\n```powershell\n# Download from https://github.com/microsoft/perfview/releases\nPerfView.exe collect -ThreadTime -Duration:30\n```\n\n### Quick tips\n- **`dotnet-trace`** → best for managed-code hotspots (allocations, GC, your code)\n- **PerfView** → best when you suspect kernel, I/O, or contention issues\n- Collect for **30–60 seconds** under load — that's usually enough to spot the hot path","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"9fd1eec6-090c-4e70-96d4-fa62d641158b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about collecting a CPU trace for a .NET 8 service on Windows Server. This is a diagnostic/troubleshooting question, not a code change task. I can answer this from knowledge without needing to explore any codebase.","outputTokens":381,"requestId":"A0D2:3988B0:C0737A:EE0B56:6A0130BE"},"id":"b642f315-073d-419a-9a9f-c32e42995bc2","timestamp":"2026-05-11T01:28:41.661Z","parentId":"ddbabfcd-3ff3-4b0c-a17c-2913c8cd31f6"}
